Originally an actual mask made of dough, '''doughface''' is now a term used in a disparaging context for someone, especially a politician, who is pliable, moldable like dough.<ref> http://www.vintage-vocabulary.com/doughface.html | Vintage Vocabulary</ref>

In the years leading up to the [[American Civil War | United States Civil War]], "doughface" was used to describe Northerners who espoused sympathies with the Southern Slave Power. This would most likely be a Northern Democrat who was more allied with the ideology of Southern Democrats than that of the majority of Northerners.

Politicians frequently termed "doughface" include [[Franklin Pierce]] and [[James Buchanan]], both Presidents during the time period 1853-1861, and [[Fernando Wood]], mayor of New York City and U.S. Congressman.  They supported the Southern agenda of the free expansion of slavery into the territories, unlike Northern Democrats such as [[Stephen Douglas]], who felt that Popular Soveriegnty should be the law of the land.{{citation needed}}

